From m|ke@m@honey@218 @end|ng |rom gm@||@com  Tue Mar 26 18:15:31 2024
From: m|ke@m@honey@218 @end|ng |rom gm@||@com (Michael Mahoney)
Date: Tue, 26 Mar 2024 13:15:31 -0400
Subject: [R-sig-eco] ErrError: Non-numeric argument to binary operator,
 despite values being numeric
In-Reply-To: <CAFXQFgMwSTMr0FJheBj1q-NPrJWSp4MuKMVC4kVd2oVcf3GJng@mail.gmail.com>
References: <CAFXQFgMwSTMr0FJheBj1q-NPrJWSp4MuKMVC4kVd2oVcf3GJng@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAKpp89u0Mf_Dq2Wac5awaQD8zj8NpSRpx-s5VygAgqnURjz1dA@mail.gmail.com>

The error message is from "+" when you're trying to add things to the
pre-defined formula:
```
formula <- x ~ y
try(formula + 1)
#> Error in formula + 1 : non-numeric argument to binary operator
```

The non-numeric argument in question is the formula object. "+" has a
special meaning when used in combination with "~", but once the
formula object exists you can't add on to it with "+".

To add additional terms to a pre-defined formula, use update() (and
specifically the update.formula() S3 method):

```
update(formula, ~. + (1 | z))
#> x ~ y + (1 | z)
```

Thanks,

Michael Mahoney

